  "body": "I believe there are some differences in the Whisper PoW calculation in go-ethereum compared to what is written in [EIP-627](https://github.com/ethereum/EIPs/blob/master/EIPS/eip-627.md). I'm not sure if this is intended or not but I couldn't find any more information on why these differences are there, hence the creation of this issue.\r\n\r\n1. RLP-encoded envelope size versus sum of sizes of the individual envelope fields:\r\nThe EIP-627 mentions: `where size is the size of the full RLP-encoded envelope.`\r\nThe go-ethereum code seems to not use the RLP-encoded envelope size: https://github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/blob/8711e2b6366109912057e8fb20add325a1051a4e/whisper/whisperv6/envelope.go#L54\r\nWhich is used in `calculatePow`: https://github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/blob/8711e2b6366109912057e8fb20add325a1051a4e/whisper/whisperv6/envelope.go#L139\r\nWhile this will probably not create a huge difference in size, it can still be different.\r\n\r\n2. PoW Hash:\r\nThe EIP-627 has following line of code:\r\n`fn pow_hash(envelope, env_nonce) = sha3(short_rlp(envelope) ++ env_nonce)`\r\nBut the code written in `calculatePow` and also in `Seal` does something else: there is a sha3 (keccak) digest done first on the `short_rlp` of the envelope, and then again on the resulting hash + the `env_nonce` (with some zeroes in between I guess?).\r\nWhy this difference? The `++` in the EIP does just mean append right?\r\n\r\nI realize the EIP-627 specification is still in draft, but I would like to clear this out as without a correct PoW calculation, different implementations will not be able to properly work together (especially with different PoW hashing).",
